Jsom file format (for the Matrex programming language)

Variable place holders:
<$S> : A string variable place holder
<$I> : An integer variable place holder
<$L> : A list/array variable place holder

Assignings:
-> : *Base symbol for assigining value from the operation on the left the right
	&# : data for output of operation (usually the output of the executed script)
	&€ : data for content of operation (usually the content of a file or script)
	&¤ : data for raw value of operation (usually the raw value of the written text in the jsom file)
		&¤S: raw string value
		&¤I: raw integer value
		&¤L: raw list value
	$S : passing string data as a variable to an operation
	$I : passing integer data as a variable to an operation
	$L : passing list/array data as a variable to an operation

<- : *Base symbol for assigining value from the operation on the right to the left
	&# : data for output of operation (usually the output of the executed script)
	&€ : data for content of operation (usually the content of a file or script)
	&= : data for content of operation json_data (usually the content of the referenced json_data)
	&¤ : data for raw value of operation (usually the raw value of the written text in the jsom file)
		&¤S: raw string value
		&¤I: raw integer value
		&¤L: raw list value
	$S : passing string data as a variable to an operation
	$I : passing integer data as a variable to an operation
	$L : passing list/array data as a variable to an operation
	[**Any variable type**] : passing a list/array of different types of data as a variable to an operation
		
##Example of basic assignings
-&#> : Assign the output data from an operation on the left to the right
<&€- : Assign the content data from an operation on the right to the left

##Example of advanced assignings
-&¤$I> : Assign the raw value data from an operation as an integer variable to the right from the left
<&#$S- : Assign the output data from an operation as a string variable to the left from the right
-[$S, $S, $I, $L]> : Assign a list/array of values from an operation as varaibles to the right from the left - **not developed yet

Instruction variables:
A& : The reference for the used AI model
	&I: the input assignment (the entry to pass the data to the input field of the AI model)
	&O: the output assignment (the entry where the output data of the AI model is located)
	&D: the 'decision' assignment (the entry where the AI model from its output can make a decision about a provided list of data)
	&M: the model assignment (the entry where you can define the used AI model)
	&P: the prompt assignment (the entry to specify a specific user prompt for the AI model in the given field)
	&S: the 'service' assignment (the entry to specify the provider of the ai models using the LiteLLM module)
**Any combination of capital letters**& : A custom reference for a separate variable
	&S: the script assignment (the entry to store a script in the varaible) - Functions will automatically extracted in to the &F function from this entry
	&F: the 'function' assignment (the entry where a function can be chosen to be executed from a list | useful for accessing certain functions from a script that was stored in the variable)
	&J: the 'json' assignment (the entry where a json value can be chosen | useful for accessing certain json data from a json that was stored in a variable) - **not developed yet
	&V: the value assignment (the entry for the value the variable holds - independent from the data type)
	&P: the picture assignment (the entry where a raw image data can be stored or accessed) | useful for projects with image generation or image manipulation

Command variables:
&= : The reference for the json data value (It can only reference to the command with a json output on the line)

Instruction symbols:
|>**Any reference or plain text**<| : The string that gets added to the shell (These are the raw texts that gets pasted in the terminal and executed at the end of the command)
(> |>**Any reference or plain text**<|, |>**Any reference or plain text**<| <) : Multiple separate strings that gets added to the same shell command (These are the raw texts that gets pasted in the terminal and executed at the end of the command)
(**Any continuation of a json access**) : Multiple data value accesses executed sequantially (Useful for accesing and executing multiple values from the same tree on different branches) - **not developed yet
[**Any continuation of a json access**] : Multiple data value accesses executed parallel (Useful for viewing multiple values from the same tree on different branches) - **not developed yet

Json array operations:
ˇ: or (either the default (first in order) or the one specified in command call) **not developed yet
^: and **not developed yet
**array value**$ : The place the variable will be passed on **not developed yet

Execution logics:
[(**Any command**, **Any command**)] : Multiple commands executed sequantially in a single function
[**Any command**, **Any command**] : Multiple commands executed in separate shells at the certain function (useful for parallel tool use with AI too)

